default2.default              defaultWhat is the rationale for the Government’s proposals to devolve to a local level decision-making odefaultn transport expenditure? What are the advantages and disadvantages of the Government’s approach? Are there better models?default&#xa0;default2.1
default              
defaultThe rationale for the Government’s proposals to devolve decision-making on transport expenditure to a local level is to enable lo
defaultcal people and organisations, through elected representatives
default, 
defaultstatutory bodies
default and business representatives (through LEPs)
default, to have a greater say in how 
defaultfunding is spent at a local level
default. The County Council welcomes this general principle.
default2.2
default              
defaultThe 
defaultdevolution of transport expenditure to local level decision-making organisations allows for their local knowledge and experience to be applied and used more directly to overcome local issues. This provides for a local assessment and application of a projec
defaultts benefits at a local level against locally relevant criteria, while still enabling wider national priorities to be taken in to account (although with less influence on final funding decisions).
default2.3
default              
defaultThe stability of this devolved funding is critical to th
defaulte long-term success of local decision making for transport expenditure. Having overcome initial challenges, as identified below, to develop effective organisations and structures, 
defaultit is important that 
defaultdevolved funding at a local level 
defaultis maintained to 
defaultsupp
defaultort longer-term priority setting, programme management and delivery to address local barriers to growth.
default2.4
default              
defaultThe council would, additionally, support a greater level of devolved funding and decision making to further enhance local accountability.
default While the
default current level of devolved funding and decision making is to be welcomed, there remains an element of centralised priority setting that may, on occasion, be in conflict with well established, evidence-based locally supported improvements. The council would
default, therefore, support a greater level of devolution to be considered that provided for a greater level of local decision making with less prescription from Government.
default2.5
default              
defaultA 
defaultkey challenge with
default this approach has been in ensuring that local statutory bodies a
defaultnd decision makers have 
defaultthe capacity
default and specialist staff
